Intuition
after looking at question i realized it is a sliding window problem but the window size is not fixed , my strategy to calculate minimum subarray was to first find the number of subarrays required that my window sum becomes equal or greater than or equal to target like a company hires employees and stops when the work starts getting done , then i fire emplyoyee checking if my work is still getting done or not , if my work is being done , i fire more employees at the end i see how many minimum employees i need so that my work gets done

Approach
i create 2 pointers one for hiring and one for firing , hiring is done by high and firing is done by low
low and high = 0
i create a variable to check min_length and initalize it to infinity
window_sum = 0

traverse array till we hire all the employees that is
while high < len(arr):
we start by hiring as there is no employee initally
window_sum += arr[high]

inside loop i check if i reach total >= target 
    then i calculate length of subarray at which my work has start to begin , i compare it with man_length (in first time it is initalized and then we compare it with new lengths after firing process) 
    then we fire employees as window_sum -= arr[low]
    increase low count by 1

increase high count by 1
edge case condition if all the employees combined are not able to finish the job return zero

else return min_length

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)

Space complexity:
O(1)

Code
class Solution:
    def minSubArrayLen(self, target: int, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        high = 0
        low = 0
        min_length = float('inf')
        n = len(nums)
        total = 0

        while high < n:
            total = total + nums[high]

            while total >= target:
                length = high - low + 1
                min_length = min(min_length ,length)
                total = total - nums[low]
                low += 1
            
            high += 1
            
        if min_length == float('inf'):
            return 0

        else:
            return min_length
